<h>Star Princess Turned Away from Falklands Due to Noro-Virus</h>
<p>January 17, 2012 By: Susan Young 
<p> was turned away from calling at in the on Saturday, because the government said it was unprepared to deal with a noro-virus outbreak and had limited resources to deal with such a situation.</p>
<p> spokeswoman called the government's response totally unwarranted. No Princess ship has ever been denied entry into a port based on incidences of ill passengers and crew onboard, she said.</p>
<p> Noro-virus is essentially the stomach flu; symptoms of diarrhea and vomiting are often severe but usually disappear within 48 hours. Except for the elderly, young children or those with severe medical issues, the virus usually is harmless. Over the past few years, cruise lines have a well-established protocol for dealing with cases of noro-virus onboard ships.</p>
<p>Health groups, such as the and 's , generally encourage ports to offer support to vessels arriving with ill people. In addition, only 74 passengers and crew (about two percent of those on board) had been reported ill; that's below the three percent level the CDC considers as an outbreak. The Falklands' chief medical officer made the decision after consulting with a U.K. microbiologist. </p>
<p> An outbreak in the Falkland Islands would put enormous pressure on our limited medical resources, and jeopardize other scheduled cruise visits, a government statement said. Politically speaking, and the U.K. long adversaries for control of the remote islands off the coast of are in the midst of a diplomatic row. Argentina calls the Falklands by a different name, the . The two countries went briefly to war over the islands in 1982, with the British maintaining control. Now, , and are supporting Argentina by turning away ships flying the Falklands flag. Apparently many citizens of those countries were passengers on Today, January 17, calls in , Argentina. The 14-day cruise ends Jan. 21. </p>
